        "comment": {
            "name": "comment",
            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/32899",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=shahar",
                        "name": "shahar",
                        "displayName": "Shahar Evron",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "It is of course arguable whether this is the right thing to do. I don't really know - however keep in mind that PHP's default behavior (of SSL streams) is *not* to verify such things. \n\nThen again, we can discuss this when the time comes :)",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=shahar",
                        "name": "shahar",
                        "displayName": "Shahar Evron",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2009-07-24T03:25:32.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-07-24T03:25:32.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/32900",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=tgelf",
                        "name": "tgelf",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Gelf",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Let me re-post some older comments:\n\n> Unfortunately switching validation on per default is not an option as\n> it would break currently working applications. I would suggest to change\n> this with ZF 2.0 - as other libs \/ languages I know (CURL, Java, C# etc)\n> are doing so out of the box. And in my believes this is the only correct\n> way of using HTTPS. If someone wants to do insecure things he is free to\n> do so, but he has to explicitly switch checks off.\n\n(see http:\/\/www.nabble.com\/Validating-SSL-server-certs---using-CA-certs-p20225319.html for full post)\n\n> I don't know which Zend_Service_Whatever-Classes are based on HTTPS\n> (a quick grep showed Amazon_Ec2, Delicious, ReCaptcha), probably all of\n> them are using Zend_Http_Client - with insecure defaults. And I'm pretty\n> sure others will follow.\n> \n> Therefore I strongly suggest changing default settings with ZF 2.0. Many\n> developers just don't realize that self-signed certificates lead HTTPS ad\n> absurdum - and also not verifying signed ones does. If someone insists on\n> using useless certificates he can do so. But he needs to be made aware of\n> doing something REALLY bad (and shall be forced into explicitely allowing\n> this in his own code).\n\nI do NOT think it is arguable what the default setting should look like. Other\nlanguages \/ frameworks behave correct, even cURL (also in PHP) does so.\nAnd I don't think taking PHP's scary defaults as a reference would be a good\nidea.\n",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=tgelf",
                        "name": "tgelf",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Gelf",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2009-07-24T03:42:44.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2009-07-24T03:42:44.000+0000"
                },
                {
